---
import PageLayout from "../layouts/PageLayout.astro";
import { SITE } from "../lib/site";
---

<PageLayout
  title="Editorial Policy & Ethics"
  lede="The rules we operate by, written down so you can hold us to them."
>
  <h2>Independence</h2>
  <p>
    Editorial decisions — what we cover, how we cover it, what conclusions we
    draw — are made by the editorial team alone. Advertisers, sponsors, and
    sources don't see stories before publication and don't get approval over
    anything, including stories about themselves.
  </p>

  <h2>Sponsored content</h2>
  <p>
    Anything paid for is labelled "Sponsored" clearly, at the top, in a visual
    treatment distinct from editorial. We don't publish advertorials disguised
    as analysis, and we don't accept payment for coverage, placement, or
    favourable framing. If a sponsor's company appears in our editorial
    coverage, the sponsorship is disclosed in that piece.
  </p>

  <h2>The Hard Part is never paid</h2>
  <p>
    Stories in <a href="/the-hard-part/">The Hard Part</a> are never paid
    placements, never PR-arranged image pieces, and never published in exchange
    for anything. Every story goes through the same editorial filter: real
    numbers, real mistakes, specific decisions. Subjects see their quotes for
    accuracy checking — not for approval, softening, or removal of
    inconvenient details. If a story reads flattering, that's an editing
    failure, and we'd like to <a href="/contact/">hear about it</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Corrections</h2>
  <p>
    When we get facts wrong, we correct the piece and append a note saying what
    changed and when. Significant errors get flagged in the next newsletter as
    well. We don't silently edit published stories, and we don't delete pieces
    because someone finds them inconvenient. Spotted an error? Write to
    <a href={`mailto:${SITE.contactEmail}`}>{SITE.contactEmail}</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Sources</h2>
  <p>
    We grant anonymity when naming a source would expose them to real
    professional risk, and we tell you when we've done so and why the source is
    in a position to know. Numbers from anonymous sources get corroborated
    before we print them or they get framed as unverified.
  </p>

  <h2>Conflicts of interest</h2>
  <p>
    Writers disclose financial interests — investments, advisory roles,
    employment history — in any company they cover, in the piece itself. Where
    a conflict is material, someone else writes the story.
  </p>
</PageLayout>
